<DOC><DOCNO> AP890127-0225 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-27-89 2210EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0792)--officialssaynewjerseyishavingitswarmestjanuaryinthreeyears.01-27 0458</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0792,0464</SECOND><HEAD>Snow And Rain In The Southern High Plains</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-8, `Very cold ..., with 3 grafs to RECAST, fixtypos; picks up 9th graf: `In the national ...</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A low pressure system over southwest New Mexico spread snow, rainand drizzle and thunderstorms across New Mexico on Friday, andAlaska's cold snap continued with record lows and wind chills downto 100 degrees below zero.   Snow showers swung from the Great Lakes into northern NewEngland, but fair weather and seasonally mild temperatures prevailedfrom the northern and central Plains to the mid-Atlantic states.   In New Mexico, up to 6 inches of new snow was measured Friday atLos Alamos, with additional accumulations up to 4 inches expected.Showers and a few thunderstorms spread across west-central andsouthern Texas.   Snowshowers ranged across New York into Vermont.   Very cold air continued to dominate much of central and northernAlaska. For the eighth day, Fairbanks stayed colder than 40 degreesbelow zero and three places set all-time record low temperaturesovernight.   McGrath reported minus 74 degrees, breaking the old mark by 10degrees; Tanana fell to minus 76 degrees and Galena had a low of 68degrees below zero, while 10 to 15 mph winds put winds chills colderthan 100 degres below zero.   The low in the nation Friday morning was 27 degrees below zero atGunnison, Colo. Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST rangedfrom zero at Lake Yellowstone, Wyo., to 80 degrees at Miami and FortMyers, Fla.   In the national forecast for Saturday, rain and thunderstormswill be likely across the central and southern Plains into themiddle Mississippi Valley. Showers will be scattered from centraland southeast Texas into the lower Mississippi Valley, and acrosscentral and northern Illinois.   Snow will be widespread from northwest Kansas and southwestNebraska into the eastern half of Colorado and northeast New Mexico.Rain will change to snow across southwest Kansas and the westernOklahoma Panhandle.   High temperatures will be in the 30s and 40s across much of thenation west of the Mississippi River and in the 50s and 60s east ofthe Mississippi River; in the teens and 20s over southern Idaho andnortheast Nevada, and across northern Maine; in the 30s from thenorthern Plains through the northern Great Lakes into southern NewEngland; in the 40s from the lower Great Lakes to the northern halfof the mid-Atlantic Coast; in the 50s and 60s from northern andcentral California through the southern Rockies, and much of Texasinto the lower Mississippi Valley; in the 70s over the Los Angelesbasin, and from the central Gulf Coast through much of Florida.</TEXT></DOC>